h, Cople, Central Bedfordshire Unitary Authority, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England":"Pavenham, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1509–10 Jun 1560":"1509–10 June 1560","1505–1559":"1505–1559","1537–1558":"1537–1558","1509–1560":"1509–1560","1558":"1558","10 Jun 1560":"10 June 1560","about 1537":"about 1537","1560":"1560","1509":"1509","9 Jun 1558/59":"9 June 1559","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","1559":"1559","Edworth, Bedfordshire, England":"Edworth, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","London, Greater London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Stafford, Stafford Borough, Staffordshire or Edworth, Cople, Central Bedfordshire Unitary Authority, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England":"Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Agnes Ann Spencer was born in 1509, in Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Baron John Edward II de Spencer-van Stofold, Bedfordshire, Baron Spencer of Stofold, Bedfordshire, MP, High Sheriff of Northamptonshire. She died on 10 June 1560, in Edworth, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 51, and was buried in London, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1509–10 Jun 1560":"1509–10. juuni 1560","1505–1559":"1505–1559","1537–1558":"1537–1558","1509–1560":"1509–1560","1558":"1558","10 Jun 1560":"10. juuni 1560","about 1537":"umbes 1537","1560":"1560","1509":"1509","9 Jun 1558/59":"9. juuni 1559","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","1559":"1559","Edworth, Bedfordshire, England":"Edworth, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, Greater London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Stafford, Stafford Borough, Staffordshire or Edworth, Cople, Central Bedfordshire Unitary Authority, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pavenham, Bedfordshire, England":"Pavenham, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1509–10 Jun 1560":"1509–10. kesäkuuta 1560","1505–1559":"1505–1559","1537–1558":"1537–1558","1509–1560":"1509–1560","1558":"1558","10 Jun 1560":"10. kesäkuuta 1560","about 1537":"noin 1537","1560":"1560","1509":"1509","9 Jun 1558/59":"9. kesäkuuta 1559","1505":"1505","1537":"1537","1559":"1559","Edworth, Bedfordshire, England":"Edworth, Bedfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, Greater London, England":"London, E